		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<HR>
<BR>
<P></P>
<P>Battleblade-Xegony wrote<img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-surprised.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0>lav,<BR><BR>I appreciate the fact that you are explaining a point of view, but let's examine it a bit.<BR><BR>"If you look at Kunark, Velious, and Luclin, players had the vast majority of the storyline and zones available before guilds needed the large raid forces to continue."<BR><BR>While any player could walk into the numeric majority of the content before Kunark, heroic encounters were exclusively the relm of those who raided. Joe Casual did not see Vox, Naggy, CT, Inny, the Maestro of Rancor and dozens upon dozens of other named mobs and encounters.</P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00>I didn't see those mobs you listed as soon as the hardcore crowd did, but I was killing some of them prior to Velious while I was around lvl 50. In those days, pick up raids and raids sponsored by small to mid-size guilds were fairly common for Hate and Fear. I haven't seen a pick up raid announced for anything but Emoush in months on my server.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00>I'm not disputing that raid content is meant to be the most challenging content to face and that only those willing <STRONG><EM>and able </EM></STRONG>to face the highest risk should reap those highest rewards when they beat it.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00></FONT><BR>"Each of those expansions only had ONE locked zone that required a raid force to access."<BR>SoE didn't "lock" it and forgot to give casuals the key. There are two kinds of content that require completing prerequisites before you can take it on and in both cases the reasons the content is "locked" are valid:<BR><BR>Sleepers Tomb/Veeshan's Peak/NToV type content - rather than have these zones resemble KC or the Estate of Unrest with casual players constantly training half the zone, these were set aside as high level content.<BR><BR><FONT color=#ffff00>Minor nit-pick - ToV isn't a keyed zone. You may have needed a raid to survive in the north wing and a small raid for the Halls of Testing, but anyone could zone in. (Though there is a level requirement, maybe 46 like the old Planes?)</FONT></P>
<P>PoTime/Tacvi raid progression content - there are raids that must be completed to get to harder raids ad infinitum to reach end expansion RAID content.<BR><BR>In both cases, access to the the mobs that drop better gear is a reward for accomplishment.<BR><BR>I'm not opposed to some raid targets being right out in the open wether it be Vox or Velitorkin, but I can't see that the entire game MUST or even should be that way.<BR><BR>The raid progression content is not "locked". There is content that you must win your way past by completing other content first.</P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00>Well, that is what I mean by "locked". You need some sort of "key" to open the door to that content. And while I certainly can see why raiders may like the kind of raid progression content that gives them a clear set of goals to knock down before moving on to the next step, that's exactly what players in smaller guilds are asking for. Lunrak referred to it as a 'shotgun' effect in how smaller raid forces jump from expansion to expansion&nbsp;without any particular progression targets except that their looking to kill mobs that have upgrades.</FONT><FONT color=#cccccc><FONT color=#66ff00><BR></FONT><BR>I understand that getting to PoTime is a major pita. The question is, should everybody that pays $19.95 have Quarm loot or should you have to accomplish the same things thousands of other players have to get there? Should the expert slopes at your local ski resort be widened, smoothed, and the angle of the slope reduced, etc. or are the intermediate trails sufficient to meet the needs of intermediate skiers?</FONT></P>
<P>Message Edited by Battleblade-Xegony on <SPAN class=date_text>11-07-2005</SPAN> <SPAN class=time_text>06:21 AM</SPAN> 
<P>
<HR>

<P></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>No one with any sense is suggesting that buying an expansion entitles them to end-game loot. But your second question is the relevent one. Is there enough content for smaller guilds (those capable of wielding 3-5 groups for a raid, maximum) to progress through? And if there is enough content, is it set up to be truly progressive, or do you have to jump around such that the only logic to chosing the next target is whether it provides the next step in gearing up? Expansion's raid progressions are designed to take the raiders through the story, casual players should have as much of an opportunity to improve their characters in a logical manner through an expansion's storyline as anyone else, though certainly the endgame raiders will be the only ones to witness directly&nbsp;the final chapters. (Just like only the raiders got to give Tormax Yelinak's head or wake the Sleeper.)</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
