<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=warriorbalance&message.id=12335#M12335">184</a> of 332
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 263 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<P>Battleblade-Xegony wrote:<BR>While there are exceptions and sporatic improvements, I think the "storyline" amd lore aspect is being overblown a bit. Guilds kill Hanvar because he's there and drops ph4t l3wts plain and simple.</P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff66>While that is true the lore aspect of it is part of it.&nbsp; If all raid content was nothing more than hopping from random zone A to random zone B providing uber gear, I think it wouldn't be as popular as a steady progression that is linear.</FONT><BR><BR>PoTime, which is maybe requires the most involved flagging that we've discussed (and the best storyline IMO), isn't necessarily a problem as an endzone. IF 24 people could get there, then could could knock off a couple of Phase 1 instances and call it a day. But like Tacvi, I seriously doubt a 24 person raid force could make it to this zone.<BR><BR>Anguish, VT, SSra, VP, and ST are somewhat somewhat simular in this respect. It does not necessarliy take a 54 person raid to beat the prerequisites and zone in. However, actually killing something in these zones may be beyond the capabilities of a 24 person raid (and may not - anguish augs are obtainable by 24).<BR><BR>It MIGHT seem reasonable to ask SoE to look at making more prerequisite progression content not need 50ish player to beat. But let me ask, are you proposing straining larger guild unity by making this stuff 24 person content or letting it remain 54 but (barely) doable by 24 and trivial to 54? IMO, there should NOT be 2 widely disparate paths to PoTime nor 2 versions of PoTime once you get there.<BR><FONT color=#ffff66>Actually what is being suggested is something that would not interfere with the larger guilds at all.&nbsp; The content tuned for them would continue to exist as it has in the past.&nbsp; This would merely provide a parallel, but weaker version of the same content with weaker loot.&nbsp; The additional advantage is that the larger guilds would have a better pool of players to recruit from as well since the effort of the guild to regear and flag these people would be lessoned as&nbsp;a result.&nbsp; You say there shouldn't be 2 widely disparate paths to PoTime no 2 version of PoTime, but imo there has to be something other than what we have now.&nbsp; 24 person raiding is virtually a joke to this point, because it is not linear, therefore not well defined as a gear up path for those raiding forces.&nbsp; People want to do the linear progression, that is why DoN and DoD are nice in that they have linear group progression.&nbsp; Mid tier raiding is random not because of lack of skill, but do to the design of raid content.</FONT></P>
<P><BR>IMO however, a whole lot of content IS available to 24 person raids depending on their capability. This is particularly true of OoW - Fertha, Chalik, King and Queen, and the open zone targets in WoS is a fair amount of content that is acessable but some not yet doable. But, add to this MPG group activities, getting Epic 1.5's and older content that has been mudflated and there is both content and to the same extent up until the point a 24 person force can no longer prgress, the same exact storyline as everyone else experiances.<BR><FONT color=#ffff66>While there is alot of content that can be tackled by a 24 person force, again it is not linear.&nbsp; Additionally it is all open content, therefore you are dealing with additional issues in tackling those raids (i.e. groups training the raid or the raid interfering with group activities).</FONT></P>
<P><BR>While I do think SoE should pay attention to smaller unit raiding and the storyline/progression in general, I don't think that smaller guilds have been neglected by SoE as much as they have neglected to apply themselves to beating existing raid content in the first place. Opprotunity and effective effort are directly proportional.</P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff66>It is a common misconception to assume smaller units aren't applying themselves.&nbsp; It is akin to the misconception that hardcore raiders are jerks.&nbsp; The problem isn't that the opportunity doesn't exist, it is in the implementation of that opportunity.&nbsp; Make the mid tier raiding content linear, providing intermediate gear and then you have a solution that makes sense.&nbsp; I agree that effort is important, but there has to be effective opportunity that is based on what the player base expects.&nbsp; By design both group and raid content has been linear.&nbsp; Players see things in that light, understand it, and therefore are most comfortable with it.&nbsp; When you make the path of progression through mid tier raiding more scattered, it becomes muddled, less clear, and certainly less effective.&nbsp; If it is linear people can wrap themselves around that idea, because there is a logic to it.&nbsp; It makes sense in PoP that you go through each zone to get access to the next in this linear manner, but there is no pre-defined line of raiding in the events some have listed above.&nbsp; A mob here a mob there, can do in any order whatsoever, makes no difference, only the power of your force determines if you move on to the next mob.&nbsp; While some might like that idea, I would rather be involved in the linear progression.&nbsp; If it isn't available without a major life change, then the opportunity isn't effective, therefore no amount of effort on my part will matter.</FONT></P>
<P>Message Edited by Battleblade-Xegony on <SPAN class=date_text>11-08-2005</SPAN> <SPAN class=time_text>11:58 AM</SPAN><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<DIV>I would like to ask again why those opposed to this idea are opposed.&nbsp; Do you see it as taking away what the more powerful force can achieve? Do you see it as creating a strain on the ranks of large guilds?&nbsp; Is it something I'm not even seeing? Please consider this idea in no way takes out content you currently enjoy, nor future raid content that you would enjoy tuned for the size forces you currently employ.&nbsp; It merely provides an alternative to raiding in a force of that size for those that are unable to for any reason and want the same kind of linear progression it offers.</DIV><p>Message Edited by Lunrak on <span class=date_text>11-08-2005</span> <span class=time_text>02:47 PM</span>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							<img src=" http://mywebpages.comcast.net/lunrak/LunrakSOESig.gif"><br><A href= "http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=1125375">Lunrak of Fennin Ro</A><br><br>If you have to tell me how uber you are...then you aren't. <br>If you are uber I will already know, and wont need you to remind me.
							</div>
								
		</td></tr>
