<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=warriorbalance&message.id=12337#M12337">186</a> of 332
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 251 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			"Do you see it as taking away what the more powerful force can achieve?"<br>No, it is however making a second raid game and moving resources from rading as it has alwas been defined. To a great extent in OoW and DoN SoE asceeded to the wishes of more casual players by putting a lot of content right out in the open and not requiring flags - and it largely didn't matter - they still didn't beat the content.<br><br>Now you suggest content should be linear. That implies exactly the kind of progression where some content is locked way until you complete previous content that many casuals previously objected to.<br><br>Effort that is not productive put into casula raiding and content is counter-productive since it is done insted of other effort, like PoTime, that has defined EQ and IS the reason people play even if they personally haven't achieved it.<br><br>"Do you see it as creating a strain on the ranks of large guilds?"<br>Absolutely. On raid days, the guild assembles to raid - all 45-60 players present. Every raid target created for 24 players worth doing means that is either ignoed if possible, or half the raid forces sits it out if not.<br><br>"....and want the same kind of linear progression it offers."<br>I think raids needs to stay raids and can't realistically be 1/3rd raids (18 players) or half-raids (24), etc. Neither number is more valid than the other.<br><br>I don't think producing a seperate 24-person linear alternate progression path is realistic. IMO, SoE could however design THE (one and only) progression so that it was more linear and was front loaded with 24-person half-raids. This would require guilds to hit multiple targets on raid days at the start of a release but would also allow for a common and more acessable progression.<br><br>For example, imagine that the PoTime progression encounters on the way to each of the Elemental Planes was designed for 24 players. There would have in fact been a more or less linear progression leading to endzones of sorts. Put 24 player raidable targets in each of the EP zones and other content like the Rathe Council not really doable by them that does lock out access to PoTime itself.<br><br>A progression, even a linear one, need not be seperate content nor allow casual guilds to reach either the same "endgame" content or an alternate one to be valid.<br><br>Yes, I understand quite a number of casual players and family guild members are annoyed that they have not seen Quarm, etc. But they did not see Inny, Seru, etc. when it was anything like current either. The problen was not that the content and the requirements to reach it were toooooo haaaard, but rather they did not meet them.<br><br>Want to see endgame content (either 24 person or 54 person endgame content)? Join an endgame guild or make your curreent guild into one - don't make a shallow end of the pool instead.	
		</td></tr>
