		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV><EM>No, it is however making a second raid game and moving resources from rading as it has alwas been defined. To a great extent in OoW and DoN SoE asceeded to the wishes of more casual players by putting a lot of content right out in the open and not requiring flags - and it largely didn't matter - they still didn't beat the content.</EM><BR></DIV>
<DIV>I agree that is what alot of the more casual crowd asked for, and personally I questioned that request at the time.&nbsp; I merely couldn't put my finger on what it was about PoP progression that bothered me.&nbsp; You see I understood the reasoning behind locking and flagging the zones.&nbsp; I understood the challenge needed to get the flags.&nbsp; What I didn't and still don't think is right is that one of the challenges was, at the time, amassing 72 people in order to do it.&nbsp; It was just too much for most players to ever hope for and that is a poor business decision.&nbsp; From a business point of view you don't lock out&nbsp;a major chunk of your customers from parts of your product.&nbsp; So what should have been requested at the time is exactly what some of us are bringing up now.&nbsp;&nbsp; In truth it is the same reasons people asked for the locks to be removed, unfortunately it was the wrong request imo.&nbsp; The locks should have stayed, the barriers to the keys should not have been so great.&nbsp; This would have also elminated the need for 85/15 since larger guilds trying to backflag could have done so with a smaller force instead of dedicating night after night to it as some did.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><EM>I think raids needs to stay raids and can't realistically be 1/3rd raids (18 players) or half-raids (24), etc. Neither number is more valid than the other.</EM><BR></DIV>
<DIV>Likewise there is nothing magical about the number 54 either.&nbsp; Before PoP I don't think there was a min/max number on raids, but I may be wrong there.&nbsp; PoP, its max is 72, and depending on gear and levels the min doesn't seem to be too far behind that, maybe 54ish I would guess.&nbsp; What makes 54 ideal as opposed to 24?&nbsp; Nothing other than that is what the established guilds had available at the time, they already had that size force through growing over 4-5 years, they didn't have to add 72 people to do PoP progression.&nbsp; Sure they might have had to add 12-24 riaders, but not the entire force from the ground up.&nbsp; They reached it in small chuncks over time.&nbsp; Now in order to do that kind of raiding you have to pretty much build that size force over night or continually deal with attrition as people get sick of waiting and move, that creates an even greater barrier between raiding and not raiding.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><EM>Want to see endgame content (either 24 person or 54 person endgame content)? Join an endgame guild or make your curreent guild </EM></DIV>
<DIV><EM>into one - don't make a shallow end of the pool instead. </EM></DIV>
<DIV><EM></EM>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>This is the kind of comment though that makes people really question your reasoning and why we simply don't think hardcore raiders grasp the issue.&nbsp;&nbsp; Building a raid guild was never easy, in fact I'm not even sure it was intentional at the outset of guild creations, but in today's game I would say building a raid force is even more difficult in that you have 4-5 guilds that presently raid GoD, OoW, and DoN end zone content&nbsp; on a given server with about 40 or 50 other guilds competing for the remainder of the population.&nbsp; So taking into account the time involved in getting that size force together you will continually lose people to the guilds already doing the raiding for the most part, as a result the guilds wanting to reach that size by and large wont, and have very little hope of ever achieving that.&nbsp; The last guild I saw do it started 2 years ago, they broke time 2 months ago.&nbsp; That is one guild out of 40-50 that started out small since Pop released.&nbsp; There is no 24 person end game content you mention, which is what is being suggested, it needs to be there.</DIV>
