			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=warriorbalance&message.id=12341#M12341">189</a> of 332
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 227 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<HR>
</P>
<P>Battleblade-Xegony wrote:<BR>"Do you see it as taking away what the more powerful force can achieve?"<BR>No, it is however making a second raid game and moving resources from rading as it has alwas been defined. To a great extent in OoW and DoN SoE asceeded to the wishes of more casual players by putting a lot of content right out in the open and not requiring flags - and it largely didn't matter - they still didn't beat the content.<BR><BR>Now you suggest content should be linear. That implies exactly the kind of progression where some content is locked way until you complete previous content that many casuals previously objected to.<BR><BR>Effort that is not productive put into casula raiding and content is counter-productive since it is done insted of other effort, like PoTime, that has defined EQ and IS the reason people play even if they personally haven't achieved it.<BR><BR>"Do you see it as creating a strain on the ranks of large guilds?"<BR>Absolutely. On raid days, the guild assembles to raid - all 45-60 players present. Every raid target created for 24 players worth doing means that is either ignoed if possible, or half the raid forces sits it out if not.<BR><BR>"....and want the same kind of linear progression it offers."<BR>I think raids needs to stay raids and can't realistically be 1/3rd raids (18 players) or half-raids (24), etc. Neither number is more valid than the other.<BR></P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00>72 person raids were around in POP, now it has changed to 52, and I imagine this was done from people leaving, and guild's getting downsized, maybe I'm wrong, but it's something that did happen. 52 is about what, 2/3rds of 72, so would you call that two thirds of a raid force? Really don't matter what you call it since a raid is anything more then a group, if you make a raid with two groups, or&nbsp;8 groups, it's still a raid, not a group.</FONT></P><FONT color=#ffff00>
<P><BR></FONT>I don't think producing a seperate 24-person linear alternate progression path is realistic. IMO, SoE could however design THE (one and only) progression so that it was more linear and was front loaded with 24-person half-raids. This would require guilds to hit multiple targets on raid days at the start of a release but would also allow for a common and more acessable progression.<BR><BR>For example, imagine that the PoTime progression encounters on the way to each of the Elemental Planes was designed for 24 players. There would have in fact been a more or less linear progression leading to endzones of sorts. Put 24 player raidable targets in each of the EP zones and other content like the Rathe Council not really doable by them that does lock out access to PoTime itself.<BR><BR>A progression, even a linear one, need not be seperate content nor allow casual guilds to reach either the same "endgame" content or an alternate one to be valid. <BR>Yes, I understand quite a number of casual players and family guild members are annoyed that they have not seen Quarm, etc. But they did not see Inny, Seru, etc. when it was anything like current either. The problen was not that the content and the requirements to reach it were toooooo haaaard, but rather they did not meet them.</P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00>Oh, pure bull. The guild I'm in did all of them before the bigger raids were needed. We stopped short on POP although we have done all the first tier, and most the 2nd tier's successfully. We stopped short on Luclin, never having more then a few flagged for VT, and never defeated emperor on our own to get the whole guild key'd at once. Myself, I kind of went back and forth on my Chanter and Warrior during this time period, depending on what was needed. The result is my flags and keys are scattered between two toons, but with the guild I'm in I have ST, OS, HS, all the sky keys, etc. Everything that was do-able with a smaller force we did, so I really don't see that at all. I was in Hate, Fear, etc. Way before I hit 60, Seen Inny, Seru and even had my Emperor key on my chanter before level&nbsp; 60. I'm not dissagree'ing that it's not done when forming a guild now, but back then they were done. And we never claimed to be a raid guild, always raid's were optional, and we were a family guild. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00><BR></FONT>Want to see endgame content (either 24 person or 54 person endgame content)? Join an endgame guild or make your curreent guild into one - don't make a shallow end of the pool instead.<BR></P>
<P>
<HR>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV>Now that end paragraph is what get's me everytime. "Want to see endgame content (either 24 person or 54 person endgame content)? Join an endgame guild or make your curreent guild into one..."</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>If that's how it has to be, then so be it. Your not answering the real question though, why does this bother you so much? OR does it bother you at all, and you just want a debate? I'm not sure, you say your in support of smaller "Half Raid's" (your words, not mine), then you say something like the last paragraph. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I think I do understand somewhat, what your point is though. YOU, having done the content, see many ways that WE can progress, although it's not lineor at all. You have little concern if there is a story line, although you really seemed to enjoy POP storyline, so that tells me, you actually do like them. Many of us do. Your missing something that is really important in my eyes though...... </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>When we look at content, we tend to look at expansions as a way to figure out where we are, as far as progression. If your guild is doing POP Progression, it's thought of as mid progression, if in DoN end game, your considered doing high progression, if in DOD end game, your doing cutting edge content. After the next expansion, GOD will probably be thought of as nothing more then Mid progression, if it's not already. This point is important, because weather you started at the beginning of EQ's life, or last night, you learn this in game, while playing. People talk about it openly in general, guild, and private chat channels. They talk about it in groups you get, private tells and links. Everyone that has played over a month, knows something of it. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Now, consider this when your talking about an alternate line of advancement, or progression. Most people want to start with POP, which I also believe was the overall change SOE made that made this game so popular.&nbsp; Taking into consideration how that was done, and even things&nbsp; you (BB) have posted in other forums, most people believe they must do POP before doing GOD. And in turn do GOD before doing OOW, OOW before doing DoN, and doing DoN before doing DoD. Everytime there is an expansion, we all go look at it, they become the most populated zones in the game, (Even when the new tutorial was introduced, it was the most populated zone the first day it was up).&nbsp;But the progressive routes are soon believed to be for the people that finished the other content, or at least were in it steadily. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I propose this isn't laziness, this is progressive thinking, brought on by past expansions, and what everyone learned from POP. POP was indeed do=able if&nbsp;you didn't do any other progressions, but it was alot easier for a guild that was VT gear'd to go into POP Raids and succeed, then it was someone who hadn't. Everyone learned this, the only difference now, is that we know that mudflation will allow people to do it without going into VT at this time period. GoD wasn't just a knight thing, it was everyone that thought that stuff was just tough as a (Words I do not know). The thought was you better be time gear'd, or at least EP gear'd to do them. After every new expansion is released, most feel they are just getting farther and farther behind, not looking at being able to go here and there to upgrade gear, but looking for a definitive way to progress through content. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I think you do have a point though, but it's a wild card. I'm gonna try another approach here, and see where it leads. What if there was a clear definitive path, and a story line, that led us to places that have already been brought up. Let me give an example.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>A story line that led us around content, maybe not through an expansion, but looking at all the content as a whole. Something using what's already in the game, like the stuff that Frodlin and other's have suggested us do for gear, but instead of it being solely for gear, have a storyline and a progressive path that starts to flag, key, or unlock older content as we progress through it. </DIV>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							"One falsehood destroys a thousand truths." "Do not think of yourself higher than you ought to think" "If you are not guilty of the robbery then you should not hold on to the loot!" -NOEL BRYSON, Ph

The wise discuss ideas, the normal discuss events, the ignorant discuss other's.
							</div>
								
