(your words, not mine), then you say something like the last paragraph."<br><br>Read what I wrote above and you'll understand my point of view. I have nothing against making a goodly portion of THE (one and only) raid progression path 24-person content. This provides 24-person raid content with EXACTLY the same quality of storyline and progression as higher level raiders get.<br><br>BUT sir, the we beat the expansion (24 person version), killed teh end expansion boss, etc. is not IMO right. Such a raiding party ought not walk around with such "dragon loot". They, like you did I PoP, Luclin, and every expansion since are only capable of conquering a PORTION of the raid progression path.<br><br>Want to see sucessful raiding and the end expansion bosses dead at your feet? There are guilds that accomplish this Jazzy. You don't happen to be in one, but you CAN aspire to be.<br><br>The #5 guild wants to be #4, the #20 guild on your server just broke into PoTime. There's a very clear progression from "arrived" to "getting there" to "striving" to "just don't care enough to make the effort and wanting to redefine the game to meet the semi-retired non-striving play-style I and my guild have adopted and embraced for years".<br><br>We are progression-wise all running the same race. Suggesting that you (or others) find it too arduous and unrewarding and yas want a seperate race for y'all is kinda insulting to the rest of the community.<br><br>The fact of the matter is, less hardcore players DO have pretty darned awesome equipment available to them. They DO have a lot of content and it shares the same storyline and progression that even raiders plow through. The discusion is not about storyline, linear progression, or quality of gear. It's about "it's tooo haaaard" and I can't do it." BS. I've been on a server with 6 or 8 guilds having reached PoTime. There's nothing exceptional about these players except THEY made the effort and others did NOT.	
