		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>I don't think raid guilds, as they exist now, were even the orginal game designs intent. Be that as it may, if evolved into that sort of thing. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I think they have 54 man raid limits for several reasons, one of them being they can maintain a certain difficulty level with out going overboard. I remember on povar a guild called Forces Unkown. They had 120 to 150 people in thier raids before the 72 person lockdown. They zerged like crazy, and where very successful in that way. Poor mob ran out of hps before they ran out of troops. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Some folks may think derisively of zerging, but it is a tactic in and of itself. Army ants do that, over run something with sheer numbers. The Chinese army employs that tactic as well. Skill is all well and good, but even morons can bury the best warrior with enough numbers. The smaller raids forced folks to actually use more skill, rather than just wear out mobs&nbsp;&nbsp;through attrition.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>54 is prolly the number SoE thinks is the most viable to get both small unit skills, while maintaing some of that "large force" feel. Too small and you don't require some of the organizational skills one would need to keep a larger raid forced together, plus you can't add as many extra elaments that test teamwork on a large scale. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>For example, part of the test in Inkutu is getting 4 groups of 10+ peeps, into 4 seperate rooms to say a phrase to 4 seperate mobs, at the same time. All this, while fighting off traps that release multiple mobs all over the place. ( I so hate the stonemite test by the way, dang&nbsp;I see those in my sleep)</DIV>	
		</td></tr>
