<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=warriorbalance&message.id=12349#M12349">197</a> of 332
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 188 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>I think what BB is trying to say, is that certain challanges of the game that are built for a certain number, should not be changed just because some people find the task of building those numbers daunting. In other words, if I decide to build a house with 20 rooms, I shouldn't have to build another house with 10 rooms just because some of the buyers out there can't afford the 20 room house.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Maybe it's not the best buisiness sense but as the architect I can cater to who ever I want. Some small businesses build only yaghts, that's a pretty exclusive market. If certain designers see this progression path as needing 54, then it's the players responsability to find 54, not the designers responsability to make smaller raids.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Now in my state we have 11 man highschool football and some 8 man teams. If a school becomes too small to field the 11 man teams they can go to the 8 man teams. However, they have to leave thier conferance to do so. Perhaps SoE could set up a different raid route, but you would have to leave the server your on to do so.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>My guild has done the 72 man raids and the gOD 54 man raids. LK has been around for 2 and half years or so. &nbsp;Anyhow, we are in Txevu working into Tacvi. We seldom achieve the "right" numbers for our raids, we range from 36 to 48. Yet we are still moveing. Yes,&nbsp;being level 70 does&nbsp;help, since it allows us to do some raids with smaller troop numbers. I have a lot of respect for those guilds that went through gOD progression at level 65, those are tough raids.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I mentioned before, the larger raiding enviroment is a whole different type of game than casual grouping or even family raids. It takes a certain mindset. I don't mean a better mind set, just a different mindset. It takes a certain grim fatalism to be a raider. I.E. " I am going to die this raid, prolly several times, yet I will keep at it untill I figure this encounter out and win. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Most casuals don't go out into the game enviroment expecting to die 5 times a night, sure they realize it's part of the game. But they don't generally get into groups that they know are going to die lots. Most causals, and I was one for 5 years, take a couple deaths at a camp and say,"ok this sucks, I'm out of here." </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>As an example, how many casuals would get into a group in RS to fight a named mob, only to die to the named three times or more and have the name despawn, then go back the next day and do it all over again. Not only that, but go back day in and day out for maybe weeks until you beat that named just ONCE. While&nbsp;I know there are some who can do that, many can't. They don't have the right mindset. It took me years to get into that mindset. I enjoy raiding but it took me a while to get "psyched" for it.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>My guild raids certain zones until we win, we were hitting uqua 4 times a week for several weeks at one point. You do the same thing over and over until you win. My old family guild would find a creature too tough, get wiped, and not try again for months. LK gets wiped and goes back again the next day. I suspect thats true with Frodlin's guild and BB's guild, take the loss, learn from it, try again the next day.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>	
		</td></tr>
