			>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<HR>
Battleblade-Xegony wrote:<BR><BR>I'm suggesting that they accept their situation in game and enjoy grouping if that's what they want, or being in a family guild if that floats their boat.<BR><BR>But if you want to raid, then be a tag-a-long, form a guild alliance, merge guilds, join a raiding guild, or transform your current guild into a raid guild, etc.<BR><BR>Don't suggest that merely because you and nine close friends were allowed to form a guild due to the ten player minimum that you are <U>entitled</U> to raid content, a storyline, and a progression path for ten players.<BR>
<HR>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<DIV>Entitled?&nbsp; You act like lore, storylines, and multi-group content should ONLY be reserved for those that amass large numbers.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I have no problem with keeping the most powerful loot (and a decent gap) to those who do large scale raids... I have no problem with keeping<STRONG><EM> some </EM></STRONG>lore and encounters reserved for those that do the challenging large scale raids...&nbsp; it's quite selfish of you to think that only YOU are allowed to have stories and content during your progression.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I dare wonder what it would be like if the tables were turned and group content had all the lore and raid encounters were nothing more than a spattering of large force raids with absolutely no content, storyline, or connection whatsoever.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>How adamant would you be on preserving the status quo then?</DIV>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=790661" target="_blank">
